        <body>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <head type="title">&#x201C;The Ship&#x201D; [1828&#x2010;29]</head>
                
                <div type="section" xml:id="WITNESSES">
                    <head type="section">Witnesses</head>
                    <list>
                        <item><ref type="witness" target="the_ship_msii.php"><title type="poem" corresp="#JRTHESHIP182829">&#x201C;The Ship&#x201D; [1828&#x2010;29]</title></ref> (<title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSII">MS II</title>)</item>
                        <item><ref type="witness" target="the_ship_msiii.php"><title type="poem" corresp="#JRTHESHIP182829">&#x201C;The Ship&#x201D; [1828&#x2010;29]</title></ref> (<title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSIII">MS III</title>)</item>
                    </list>  
                </div>
                
                <div type="section" xml:id="TITLE">
                    <head type="section"><title type="poem" corresp="#JRTHESHIP182829">&#x201C;The Ship&#x201D; [1828&#x2010;29]</title></head>
                    <p><persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> wrote the title as “The ship” in <title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSII">MS II</title>, and as “<hi rend="caps">THE SHIP</hi>” in MS III.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div type="section" xml:id="GENRE">
                    <head type="section">Genre</head>
                    <p>Poem. Scansion to come.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div type="section" xml:id="MAJORMS">
                    <head type="section">Manuscripts</head>
                    <p>MS II, MS III.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div type="section" xml:id="DATE">
                    <head type="section">Date</head>
                    <p>A draft appears as the first item in the handmade booklet, MS II, preceding draft of 
                        <ref type="apparatus" target="harry_and_lucy_vol3_apparatus.php"><title type="lesson" corresp="#JRHARRYANDLUCYVOL3">“Harry and Lucy, Vol. 3”</title></ref>, 
                        which Ruskin must have been written toward the end of <date when="1828">1828</date>. Substitutions in this draft are accounted for in a fair copy in MS III, 
                        so the latter witness definitely dates from a later time, 
                        likely from around <date when="1828-03-09">9 March 1829</date>, since it is included in a group of poems given that date in manuscript (see <!-- no. 47 -->).</p>
                </div>
                
                <div type="section" xml:id="COMPPUB">
                    <head type="section">Composition and Publication</head>
                    <p>Previously unpublished in its entirety. Published in part in 
                        <ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#POEMS4D1891"><hi rend="italic">Poems</hi> (4<hi rend="superscript">o</hi>, 1891)</ref>,1:???&#x2013;???; and 
                        <ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#POEMS8D1891"><hi rend="italic">Poems</hi> (8<hi rend="superscript">o</hi>, 1891)</ref>, 1:270; and
                        <ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#JRWORKSLE">Ruskin, <hi rend="italic">Works</hi></ref>, 2:264n.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div type="section" xml:id="DISCUSSION">
                    <head type="section">Discussion</head>
                    <p>See the <ref type="apparatus" target="look_at_that_ship_apparatus#DISCUSSION">discussion of an earlier poem, <title type="poem" corresp="#JRTHESHIP1827">&#x201C;The Ship&#x201D; <hi rend="italic">and</hi> &#x201C;Look at That Ship&#x201D; [1827]</title></ref>. 
                        Ruskin was inspired to rewrite this earlier poem during the family <ref type="note" subtype="contextual" target="tour_of_1828_note.php">tour of 1828</ref>. 
                        As Ruskin remarks in the 
                        <ref type="apparatus" target="travel_itinerary_and_tour_notes_apparatus.php"><title type="manual_guide" corresp="#JRTRAVELITINERARY1828">Travel Itinerary and Tour Notes [1828]</title></ref>, 
                        the family, when crossing from Portsmouth to the Isle of Wight, could see the “place where royal george sunk,” a catastrophe incorporated into the revised poem. 
                        Helen Viljoen cites <persName corresp="#TPNATURALIST">Thomas Pennant</persName> (<date notBefore="1726" notAfter="1798">1726&#x2013;98</date>), A Journey from London to the Isle of Wight (1801), 
                        which directs visitors to the topmasts of the wreck, still visible above the water. The disaster occurred in 1782, and was attributed to poor seamanship, 
                        as Ruskin’s poem implies.</p>
                    
                    <p>At line 21 of the MS III version of <title type="poem" corresp="#JRTHESHIP182829">&#x201C;The Ship&#x201D; [1828&#x2010;29]</title>, 
                        a line that starts a new page (p. 40) in that manuscript, Ruskin abruptly reduces the size of his lettering and squeezes the lines closer together, 
                        possibly suggesting that he was running out of room for this fair copy. Nothing in the MS II draft indicates that Ruskin suddenly decided to lengthen the poem. 
                        In MS III, perhaps he had already begun to fair-copy 
                        <ref type="apparatus" target="sonnet_to_the_sun_apparatus.php"><title type="poem" corresp="#SONNETTOTHESUN">"Sonnet to the Sun"</title></ref>, which follows 
                        <title type="poem" corresp="#JRTHESHIP182829">&#x201C;The Ship&#x201D; [1828&#x2010;29]</title> in MS III, but then he discovered that he had left insufficient room 
                        to complete his fair copy of the latter.</p>
                    
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="TEXTUALNOTE">
                    <head type="section">Textual Note</head>
                    <p>Body paragraph.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
